Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
report_route(25.10)                                        report_route(25.10)

Name
       report_route

Syntax
       report_route

       [-help]

       [-clock]

       [-em]

       [-fanout <integer>]

       [-fill]

       [-inst <string>]

       [-multi_cut]

       [-ndr]

       [-net <net_name>]

       [-net_length <length>]

       [-patch]

       [-pg_net <string>]

       [-secondary_pg_nets {<cellName1:pinName1>}]

       [-selected]

       [-shield]

       [-summary]

       [-via_pillar]

       [-tap_cells]

       [-track_utilization [-area {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2>}...}
       | -view_window ]

         [-layer <string>] [-include_regular_routes ]]

       Report  all  the  routing  related  information  of the design. The re-
       port_route command is used for reporting:

              * Congestion

              * Single-cut or multi-cut table for each layer.

              * Via Usage summary

              * DFM via reporting

              * Shield coverage

              * EM coverage

              * Wire length

              * Wire density

              * DRC violations

              * Statistics for selected nets

              * Track utilization

Parameter
       -area {{<lx1 ly1 ux1 uy1>} {<lx2 ly2 ux2 uy2>}...}
              Specifies the coordinates of one or more area  regions  for  re-
              porting track utilization.

              For  example,  report_route  -track_utilization  -area {299.9015
              301.332 371.8345 372.4}

              Data_type: box_list, optional

       -clock Reports statistics of clock nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -em    Reports EM statistics of nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -fanout <integer>
              Specifies the minimum fanout for limit.

              Data_type: int, optional

       -fill  Specifies the patch wire and active fill information.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes type and  default  in-
              formation for each report_route parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man report_route

       -include_regular_routes
              Reports track utilization for tracks blocked by regular wiring.

              Note: By default, the report_route command does not include reg-
              ular wiring when computing track utilization.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -inst <string>
              Specifies the instance name.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -layer <layer | layer:layer>
              Specifies  the  layer or layer range for which track utilization
              report is generated.

              For example: report_route -track_utilization -layer 1:4

              Data_type: string, optional

       -multi_cut
              Prints single-cut and multi-cut table for each  layers.  If  you
              specify the DFM via list with setNanoRouteMode -dbViaWeight then
              this option can also provide dfm via ratio

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -ndr   Reports NDR statistics of nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -net <net_name>
              Specifies the name of the net for which the report is generated.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -net_length length
              Specifies  the  minimum wire length of the net for reporting the
              net statistics. All nets whose length is more than the specified
              value are included in the report.

              Data_type: float, optional

       -patch Adds the patch length information to the report.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -pg_net <string>
              Specifies the PG net name.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -secondary_pg_nets {<cellName1>:<pinName1>}
              Specifies the secondary pg pin information. It reports the rout-
              ing length of the secondary pg pin from the grid  tap  point  to
              pin. You can use wildcards with this parameter to report all the
              secondary pg pins and sort the results in descending order.

              Use model:

              report_route -secondary_pg_nets {ENDCAP:BIASNW}

              Data_type: string, optional

       -selected
              Reports statistics for selected nets only.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -shield
              Reports statistics for shielded nets only.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -summary
              Specifies that just the summary table should be displayed in the
              report. The summary report contains:

              * Number of objects, such as cells, nets, and pins

              * Number  and  percentage of nets with one, two, three, four, or
                more terminals.

              * Names and numbers of primitives used.

              * Net length and connection length statistics

              * Total wire length and number of vias, per layer.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -tap_cells
              Reports tap cell information associated with shielded nets.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -track_utilization
              Reports the track utilization.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -via_pillar
              Reports stacking via statistics.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -view_window
              Report area in ui_view_box.

              Data_type: bool, optional

Example Report
              * The following command reports the  track  utilization  in  the
                specified  area  for  layers Metal1-Metal4 and include regular
                routes.

                report_route  -track_utilization   -area   {299.9015   301.332
                371.8345 372.4} -layer 1:4 -include_regular_routes

